HEADWORD: Cul-de-sac
<hw>Cul`-de-sac"</hw> <pr>(ku`de-s?k" ‚ü¶or‚üß kul`de-s?k")</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Culs-de-sac</plw> <pr>(ku`-
<xex>or</xex> kulz`-)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[ F., lit., bottom of a
bag.]</ety>‚ü¶br‚üß
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A passage with only one outlet, as a street closed
at one end; a blind alley; hence, a trap.</def>‚ü¶br‚üß
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>a position in which an army finds
itself with no way of exit but to the front.</def>‚ü¶br‚üß
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Any bag-shaped or tubular cavity,
vessel, or organ, open only at one end.</def>‚ü¶br‚üß
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Culerage</ent>‚ü¶br‚üß
